anada's leading disability theatre companies, emphasizing the early importance of local efforts in the absence of national coordination. Close readings of individual productions demonstrate how aesthetic choices matter and can be a source of solidarity or debate between different companies and artists. This comparative approach allows for a nuanced consideration of disability theatre's breadth and internal differences. Stage Turns highlights the diversity of disability theatre, underlining how this is critical to understanding the challenge it poses to mainstream aesthetics and to fulfilling its own artistic goals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aActors with disabilities -- Canada. 0aPeople with disabilities and the arts -- Canada. 0aTheater -- Canada -- History. 0aTheaters -- Canada -- History. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358670340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773586703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773586703/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles